<html>
<h1>JavaScript Usage Guide</h1>
<h2>The <script> Tag</h2>
<p>In HTML, for inserting JavaScript code, you should use the <script> and </script> tags. For example:</p>
<pre>
&lt;script&gt;
  document.getElementById("example").innerHTML = "Sample JavaScript";
&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>
<p>Note: JavaScript is the default scripting language in HTML, making the type attribute options optional. You may find it in older scripts as  <script type="text/javascript"></script>.</p>

<h2>JavaScript Functions and Events</h2>
<p>A block of JavaScript code representing a JavaScript function can be activated when it is "called". For instance, this can occur when a user interacts with a button. More details on functions and events will be discussed later.</p>

<h2>JavaScript in <head> or <body></h2>
<p>JavaScript scripts can be placed anywhere within an HTML document. They can be placed in <body>, <head>, or both depending on the need. It is advisable to place scripts at the end of the <body> element to boost the display speed, as script interpretation can slow down the rendering.</p>

<h2>External JavaScript</h2>
<p>Scripts can also be stored externally:</p>
<pre>
External file: scriptFile.js
&lt;script&gt;
  function exampleFunction() {
    document.getElementById("example").innerHTML = "Content Updated.";
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>
<p>You can use an external script with the script tag's src attribute:</p>
<pre>
&lt;script src="scriptFile.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>
<p>It is possible to store the script file reference in either the <head> or <body>. The script will behave as if it was exactly where the <script> tag is located. Note that external scripts cannot include <script> tags.</p>

<h3>Benefits Of External JavaScript</h3>
<p>Keeping scripts in external files offers advantages:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Separation of HTML and code.</li>
    <li>Eases HTML and JavaScript readability and maintenance.</li>
    <li>Boosts page load times with cached JavaScript files.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you want to add multiple script files to one page, use multiple script tags:</p>
<pre>
&lt;script src="scriptFile1.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="scriptFile2.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
</pre>

<h2>External Script References</h2>
<p>An external script can be linked in three different ways:</p>
<ul>
    <li>With a full URL or web address.</li>
    <li>With a file path, like /js/.</li>
    <li>Without a specific path.</li>
</ul>
</html>